  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM is a well-documented phenomenon where individuals from groups historically underrepresented in science and technology experience anxiety or stress about confirming negative stereotypes about their group's abilities. As a retired educator with a master's degree and a deep understanding of how education systems shape minds, I've witnessed firsthand how this anxiety can undermine performance. When students from minority backgrounds or those who don't fit the traditional STEM mold are told they're 'not naturally good at math,' it can trigger a psychological response that hinders their ability to think critically or solve problems. I've seen this in my own community—many talented young people in Chicago's public schools who were discouraged by teachers who assumed they couldn't handle advanced science concepts. Addressing stereotype threat isn't just about fixing a problem; it's about creating an inclusive environment where everyone feels valued. I believe the solution lies in proactive mentorship, culturally responsive teaching, and fostering a growth mindset from an early age. For instance, my own children, who are now in college, have been encouraged to explore STEM through hands-on projects that connect to their interests—whether it's building robots or coding apps for local community issues. This approach helps them see themselves as capable and confident in their abilities. Ultimately, we must shift the narrative from 'you're not cut out for this' to 'you belong here.' It’s not just a matter of policy change—it’s about empathy, understanding, and giving every child the opportunity to thrive without the weight of a stereotype.",
